        "lat": "205.— Post cladem Persis ad Marathonem illatam Miltiades, quum iam magni aestimatus esset apud Athenienses, maiore etiam fuit auctoritate. Itaque, quum petiisset septuaginta naves et exercitum, quamvis nollet dicere contra quam terram ducturus esset, diceret tamen, ‘ditaturum se eos, si sequerentur,’ Athenienses spe erecti instructas ei naves dederunt. Tum Miltiades accepto exercitu Paron navigavit; infensus enim erat Pariis ob Lysagoram quendam, qui eum olim accusaverat. Quum ad insulam pervenisset, Parios intra moenia repulsos obsedit: missoque praecone in urbem centum postulavit talenta, dicens, ‘nisi ea sibi darent, non se abducturum exercitum, donec vi cepisset urbem.’ At Parii omnibus modis operam dabant, ut urbem defenderent. Quem in finem et alia excogitabant, et, ubicunque pars muri expugnatu facilior videretur, ibi eam noctu duplo altiorem, quam prius erat, aedificabant.",
        "eng": "205.— After the defeat inflicted on the Persians at Marathon, Miltiades, who was already highly esteemed by the Athenians, was held in even higher authority. Therefore, although he requested seventy ships and an army, he would not say against which land he intended to lead them; he said, however, that he would enrich them if they followed. The Athenians, uplifted by hope, gave him the equipped ships. Then Miltiades, having received the army, sailed to Paros, for he was incensed against the Parians on account of a certain Lysagoras, who had once accused him. When he had reached the island, he besieged the Parians, repulsed within their walls: and after sending a herald into the city, demanded one hundred talents, saying, 'unless they gave them to him, he would not remove the army until he had captured the city by force.' But the Parians exerted every effort to defend the city. To this end, they thought up various means, and wherever any part of the wall seemed easier to assault, they would there build it at night twice as high as it was before."
